l 3 hours a day 6 days a week. The other kids were outside on their bikes hanging around the local park from first thing in the morning to til dusk everyday but Sunday. The diplomats kids had lots of outside activities (gymnastics, hockey, etc) and friends the other kids had nothing and barely spoke to anybody in the neighborhood. The second set of homeschooled kids also look a bit raggedy and skinny and I suspect they are abused and/or neglected. They are damn sure NOT getting educated. And of course not going to school any abuse that might be observed and documented goes unreported. &#10;Home schooling is all fine and good if the parents are up to it and actually educate. It sounds like the Powells prefer to latch on to the religious aspect (the HOME part) but are unable/unwilling to actually provide an education (the SCHOOLING part). &#10;I believe that if the public schools are really that bad then parents should dig in and help improve them not check out let them degrade even further. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1304" language="en" documentId="257" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="tunatofu" date="7/29/2013 7:19 PM GMT+0200" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/students-home-schooling-highlights-debate-over-va-religious-exemption-law/2013/07/28/ee2dbb1a-efbc-11e2-bed3-b9b6fe264871_comment.html?commentID=washingtonpost.com/ECHO/item/1375118352-702-895" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="257" notes="" title="Student’s home-schooling highlights debate over Va. religious exemption law"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="899"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="900" end="1152"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="1153" end="1304"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>